---------------
Paper summaries
---------------

- Sharma 2010: Classic persisters, originates idea of permanent resistance mutations arising from stress-induced mutagenesis in persisters
- Moore 2012: Persisters cycling slowly allows them to resist drugs that target actively cycling cells
- Knoechel 2014: Reversible random resistance, depends on altered chromatin state, but not slow-growing
- Chisholm 2015: Model based on Sharma 2010, asking whether DTP (before DTEP) is preexisting or induced by drug. Argue that slow cycling is due to stress (DNA damage) (pg 3-4)
- Hata 2016: Demonstrate that drug-tolerant cells can serve as a pool for generating permanent resistance mutations
- Ramirez 2016: Demonstrate that a wide variety of permanent resistance mutations can emerge from persister state
- Carvalho 2017: In bacteria, modeling switching between normal and persister phenotype
- Hangauer 2017: Studying unique vulnerabilities of classic persisters in a BRCA cell line
- Liau 2017: Studying unqiue features of classic persisters in a GBM cell line
- Shaffer 2017: Reversible, temporary pre-resistant state, but not slow-growing, and once drug is applied, non-genetic resistant state is not reversible
- Yaakov 2017: In yeast, found that persister phenotype was linked to previous DNA damage and subsequent erroneous repair generating new mutations
- Russo 2019: Demonstrated replication-independent dependent mutagenesis in persister cells
- Shen 2019: Classic persisters in melanoma cell line. Translational reprogramming includes upregulation of mTOR.
- Carraciolo 2020: Great review of error-prone DNA repair in cancers
- Cipponi 2020: MTOR-mediated stress-induced mutagenesis key for persisters acquiring permanent resistance mutations
- Ge 2020: Investigating and modeling development of drug resistance in TNBC
- Shaffer 2020: Showed that persister cells have groups of genes that are stably expressed together at higher than normal levels across multiple generations; source of persister markers
- Shen 2020: Great review that covers slow-growing phenotype and replication-independent mutagenesis
- Cho 2021: Slow cycling phenotype can enable cells to resist stresses e.g. chemotherapy
- Emmert 2021: Tracing the path of gene expression that leads to persisters
- Jacob Berger 2021: Argues that persister phenotype is not stochastic, and that persisters after drug exposure are more likely to keep persistence
- Oren 2021: Some persisters are slow-cycling and some aren't, and these arise from distinct lineages determined before drug treatment
- Russo 2021: Review, idea that cancer it atavistic so cancer persisters are directly related to bacterial persisters; great treatment of replication-independent mutagenesis
- Torre 2021: Found genetic factors that lead to priming for the non-reversible form of non-genetic resistance that they're studying
- Russo 2022: Modeled persister growth dynamics, estimated mutation rates, and results were consistent with persisters being drug-induced
- Isozaki 2023: Found that some drugs can induce APOBEC3A activity, leading to higher mutation rate

